## Biography

### Early Career

Ted Hamilton's journey in the entertainment industry began in 1955, where he first gained recognition performing in nightclubs and on national radio. His early career was marked by guest appearances on prominent Australian variety shows, including *The Ford Show*, *Calling The Stars*, and *The Gladys Moncrieff Show*. These appearances helped establish Hamilton as a rising star in Australia's burgeoning entertainment scene, where his charismatic stage presence and vocal talents quickly garnered attention.

### Music Career

Hamilton's music career flourished in the late 1950s and early 1960s, with several hit records that cemented his status as a notable figure in Australian jazz and pop. Among his most successful singles were "Primrose Lane" and "The Things We Did Last Summer," both of which showcased his smooth vocal style and ability to connect with audiences. However, his most commercially successful single came in 1959 with a duet alongside Ray Melton. Their cover of the US duo [Travis and Bob](/Travis_and_Bob)'s hit "[Tell Him No](/Tell_Him_No)" reached number 6 in Melbourne and became a top-20 hit in Sydney, Brisbane, and Perth. This success was a testament to Hamilton's appeal and popularity during this era.

Hamilton's musical collaborations were equally impressive. He served as the featured singer with [The Bob Gibson Band](/Bob_Gibson_(musician)) and the [Australian All-Stars](/Australian_All_Star_Jazz_Band) jazz quintet, performing alongside some of Australia's most respected musicians, including [Don Burrows](/Don_Burrows), [Terry Wilkinson](/TV_Talent_Scout), and [Errol Buddle](/Errol_Buddle). His contributions to these groups were widely recognized, earning him accolades such as being voted the best singer in jazz and pop by *Bandstand* and the music magazine *Downbeat*.

In addition to his recording career, Hamilton was a prominent figure on Australian television. He made his debut as a singer-songwriter on Australia's first variety show, broadcast on New Year's Eve in 1956 on [ABC TV](/ABC_Television_(Australian_TV_network)). Throughout the 1950s and 1960s, he appeared on numerous music variety shows across all major networks, including *The Hit Parade*, *Make Mine Music* (ABC), *Bandstand* (Channel 9), and *Sydney Tonight* (Channel 7). His involvement in the seminal variety show *Revue 61/62* further solidified his reputation as a versatile and dynamic performer.

### Television

Hamilton's transition into television was seamless, leveraging his musical background to become a regular on several influential programs. From 1961 to 1962, he was a staple on *Revue 61/62*, a television show produced by [MCA (America)](/MCA_Inc.) for the 7 Network. In late 1965, he took on the role of compere for *In Melbourne Tonight* on Monday nights on Channel 9, showcasing his ability to engage audiences beyond his musical performances.

Beyond his roles as a performer and host, Hamilton became a familiar face in Australian advertising. He lent his voice and image to some of the country's most popular and successful commercials, including campaigns for [Craven A](/Craven_A), [Mac. Robertson Land](/Mac._Robertson_Land), IC-POTA, Beautiful Rheingold, Marshall Batteries (Philip Morris' "Oh! What a Beauty"), [Coca-Cola](/Coca-Cola), [Kodak](/Kodak), and the iconic [Louie the fly](/Mortein) for Mortein. His work in advertising not only highlighted his versatility but also his widespread appeal to Australian audiences.

Hamilton's television specials were equally notable. One of the most memorable was *Ted Hamilton and [Johnny Farnham](/John_Farnham) – together again for the very first time* (June 1973), which showcased his ability to collaborate with other major Australian stars and deliver compelling entertainment.

### Sports

In a departure from his entertainment career, Hamilton also excelled in the world of sports. He was a member of the World Champion Squash team, representing [New South Wales](/New_South_Wales) and [Victoria](/Victoria_(Australia)) from 1962 to 1970. His involvement in squash at such a high level demonstrated his athleticism and competitive spirit, adding another dimension to his already multifaceted career.

### Politics and Film Career

Hamilton's influence extended into the realm of politics and activism. He starred in *Division 4* as Senior Constable Kevin Dwyer, a role that earned him critical acclaim, including Best Actor and Best Drama [Logie](/Logie_Award) awards. His performances in national theater productions further showcased his range as an actor, though specific details of these productions remain less documented.

Beyond his acting career, Hamilton was a founding member and chair of the TV-Make it Australian Committee, a lobby group dedicated to promoting Australian culture through local television productions. The committee advocated for the inclusion of Australian drama, variety, comedy, current affairs, and sports programming on national television. Their efforts were widely recognized as instrumental in preserving and promoting Australian content, with [Hector Crawford](/Hector_Crawford) and Prime Minister [John Gorton](/John_Gorton) acknowledging Hamilton and the committee as "The man, and the committee that saved Australian drama from extinction."

Hamilton's political involvement continued with his co-convening of the [Australia Party](/Australia_Party) from 1970 to 1972. He played a key role in the party's campaign for Parliament, which ultimately led to the election of several senators. Following his departure for the United States, the Australia Party evolved into the [Australian Democrats](/Australian_Democrats), led by [Don Chipp](/Don_Chipp) for many years. Hamilton was also actively involved in the "It's Time" campaign alongside [Mick Young](/Mick_Young) and Clive Holding, further demonstrating his commitment to political and social change.

However, Hamilton's career was not without controversy. In 1974, he devised and appeared in a television commercial for the Philip Morris cigarette brand "Kingford." The commercial won the Logie award for Best TV Commercial but led to his dismissal from *Division 4* due to a contract clause prohibiting series regulars from appearing in television commercials. Undeterred, Hamilton went on to host his own national variety shows on the ABC, including *Ted Hamilton's New Wave* and *Ted Hamilton's Musical World*.

Facing restrictions in Australian commercial television, Hamilton relocated his family to the United States in the mid-1970s, where he established a successful acting and corporate career. His return to Australia in 1980 was marked by an invitation from [Rupert Murdoch](/Rupert_Murdoch) to host *The Ted Hamilton Show* on the [Ten Channel](/Network_Ten) in Melbourne. However, opposition from the Broadcasting Control Board led to Murdoch abandoning the project.

In 1981, Hamilton starred in *The Pirate Movie* alongside [Christopher Atkins](/Christopher_Atkins) and [Kristy McNichol](/Kristy_McNichol). The film, which Hamilton also produced with partner David Joseph, became the first Australian movie to receive a general release in the United States, distributed across 2,500 screens by 20th Century Fox. Hamilton's financial acumen was further demonstrated through his development funding for projects such as *The Wild Duck* (starring Liv Ullmann and Jeremy Irons) for J. C. Williamson productions and *The Flight of the Navigator* for [Disney Studios](/The_Walt_Disney_Studios_(production_company)).

### Involvement in the United States and Return to Australia

Hamilton's move to the United States in 1981 marked a new chapter in his career. He was appointed chairman of two US companies involved in the placement of private capital for films and corporations, leveraging his experience and network to facilitate significant financial transactions. Additionally, he served as a senior consultant to several national companies, further expanding his influence in the corporate world.

In 2001, Hamilton returned to Australia, resuming his career in music and acting. His return was marked by a role in the international television series *Guinevere Jones* (2002), where he played the iconic character of Merlin. This role showcased his enduring talent and ability to captivate audiences, even after decades in the industry. In 2011, Hamilton was appointed as an [Australia Day](/Australia_Day) Ambassador, a role that reflected his status as a respected figure in Australian culture and society.

### Social Involvement and Honors

Hamilton's contributions to the performing arts and the community were formally recognized in the 2013 Australia Day Honours List, where he was awarded the [Medal of the Order of Australia (OAM)](/Medal_of_the_Order_of_Australia). This honor underscored his lifelong dedication to the arts and his impact on Australian culture.

